I bought my first Elton John album in 1972. I was twelve years old! I have been a fan all this time. I have been fortunate enough to see him 3 times. Twice in Albuqueque where I live and once when I went to Austin, TX for a work related training. I didn't know he was in town but an incredible friend who knew I loved Elton bought us tickets. What an unexpected treat that was! Last time he was in Albuquerque was March 22, 2017 and he performed on his 70th birthday! I wasn't sure if I would get to see him again so I bought the very best tickets. My wife and I got to see him from the 14th row, front and center. 

I'm so happy that I can see him again live tonight on Disney +. I have my corn popped and my Coke Zero, my surround sound system is all warmed up to welcome the great Sir Elton John again! 

Have a fun night, EJ Fans!

<Short Term 12 is a 2013 American independent drama film written and directed by Destin Daniel Cretton. It is adapted from Cretton's short film of the same name, produced in 2009. The film stars Brie Larson as Grace Howard, a young supervisor of a group home for troubled teenagers. The film was the first leading performance of Larson's career. Cretton based Short Term 12 on his own experience working in a group facility for teenagers. He wrote and produced a short film exploring this and later adapted it into a feature-length screenplay. While Larson and John Gallagher, Jr. won their roles after auditioning through Skype, most of the children featured in the film were cast through open casting calls. Filming took place over twenty days in Los Angeles, California in September 2012. Short Term 12 premiered on March 10, 2013 at South by Southwest, where it won the Grand Jury and Audience Awards for a Narrative Feature. The film was theatrically released in the United States on August 23, 2013, by Cinedigm. Critics praised its realism and intimacy, and especially Larson's performance and Cretton's screenplay and direction. The film is considered one of the best of 2013, appearing on several critics' year-end lists. It was listed by the National Board of Review as one of the Top Ten Independent Films of 2013. It earned three Independent Spirit Award nominations, including Best Female Lead for Larson.>

Short Term 12 is a 2013 American independent drama film written and directed by Destin Daniel Cretton. It is adapted from Cretton's short film of the same name, produced in 2009. The film stars Brie Larson as Grace Howard, a young supervisor of a group home for troubled teenagers. The film was the first leading performance of Larson's career.

Okay, so let's see, what do we have here? Insecure teenage girl, who'd lost at least one family member gets separated from her former environment, and being transported to a place with a stable. She feels so much pain she hates everyone around her, even people who are trying to comfort her. Suddenly, a wild, untameable horse appears and the girl has a sPeCiAl bond with it, although she probably had no experience with horses before. She tames the horse, she rides the horse she kinda falls in love with the horse, and then - BOOM - evil rich man gets into the picture, buys the animal, and the girl swears to get her faithful mount back. There's an unnecessary love story with a super-duper-cool handsome guy of course (because that's what average, broken-hearted teenage girls are supposed to do, dating the coolest f*ckboy in town). The only thing I'm missing is the unsymphatic, blonde, rich rival girl who does everything to keep Mr Handsome away from our heroine and humiliates her as many time as she just possibly can. So... how many times have I seen this already?

And you know what, there's nothing wrong with it. The plot is not that bad. Not original at all, but it could actually end up in something pretty amazing. But... if you can't be original with the story (which is pretty hard in these days, let's be honest, especially in the case of the horse movies) then how about... I don't know... at least TRYING to be original with the title and the name of the horse? Calling the horse and the movie Black Beauty is really disrespectful towards the original creation and its author, and since it has nothing to do with it, this title makes the fans of the novel and the older classical movie cheated. It's a beautyful black horse, there are a lot's of names which would've reflect the beauty and the ellegance of it pretty well actually. As a fan of the 1994 movie, it deeply disappoins me, that such a once great company lacks creativity this badly. But wait, what am I even talking about? It's "Disney+ ORIGINAL movie"! And this is a really catchy title, tons of people will be curious about it (especially the fans of the novel and the '94 movie), and what does that mean? That's right, even more CA$H for the company! I have an opinion about this, but I rather keep it to myself, because I don't want to be disrespectful towards the people who liked the movie and love the work of disney. 

Also, this is all my personal opinion. So even if you disagree - which is totally fine - please just share your thoughts instead of trying to force your personal views on me!

I know it's for Disney but I hope they touch on the many burdens/realities that comes with being a doctor in acute health care. It's not just walking around with clipboard and randomly saving lives. Healthcare is an intricate and delicate process. It's intense. It's an intimate connection with a patient at their most vulnerable time of their lives. It's also lots of electronic charting and notes. Its dealing with the consequences of social issues like poverty, DV etc.  I dont mind the message about balancing life and work. But without addressing the realities of medicine, you do the show a huge disservice. Acute medicine is not squeaky clean and isn't always warm and fuzzy. It's drab and cold - both cause of all the sanitization and the blasting air conditioning. But medical professionals add warmth and humanity to the environment not the other way around. Lol üòÜ I hope the show and future medical shows address these things or goes in that direction.

"Best company in the world"? Sorry, Dena (who was my teacher when I was a child and didn't remember me when I encountered her as an adult), but what about Paris Opera, Bolshoi, Mariinsky? I would say NYCB is amongst the top companies in the world, but not the best. I watched their whole season at SPAC in 2019, and it was the first time I was completely unmoved when watching "Serenade." Corps members weren't dancing together; one ran into soloist Megan LaCrone, causing a look of disgust to take over the lead's face. I felt like I was watching a rehearsal over an actual show. There was also drama that season, with Ashley Boulder being stripped of performing the lead in Coppelia by Megan Fairchild. Thus, they allowed her to perform Act 3 as an addition to one of the other shows, and one could see she was holding back tears. Technique also seemed down from previous eras, with dancers hopping pirouettes, relatively low extensions (compared to Opera or Bolshoi), un-pointed feet, and tense, elevated shoulders. 

Overall, the performances were fine. But, I wouldn't say fine is good enough to qualify them as the best in the world.

I don't think it's good to call dancers "athletes" because artists are better than athletes. 

Saying "dancers are valid because they're more similar to football players than to poets and painters" is just telling society it's okay to keep trashing poets and painters (and, you know, animators, the people who built Disney, but I guess ESPN is more important now), while giving tons of money to football players to beat each others' brains out and tell kids to do the same. 

Yes, dancers have the same physical ability as football players, but what they use it for is so much greater than football. It shouldn't be about their physical abilities, it should be about art, which is so much more important than sports.

If we say that physical ability is more important than art, can we really call ourselves human? 

Instead of calling dancers "athletes", we should be calling out the society that values athletes over artists. Dancers *are both*, but they -- and anyone -- should be more proud of the "artist" label than the "athlete" one. 

And it shows a huge problem in society that people can be more proud to be called an "athlete" than an "artist". When that's the case, how can anyone be surprised that there's so much violence in society? 

I doubt anyone's going to read this. Ugh, frightful of the word "athletes". Yes, dancers, particularly classical and contemporary dancers in this series case, possess the stamina, rigor and capabilities of athletes but unfortunately this focus on "athletes" invites one who embraces movement to focus on this aspect when the beauty is on the expressive aspect  of the form. As a devoted practitioner, teacher, advocate and champion of movement, this is disheartening. I guess people are not interested in the artistic aspect--it doesn't sell or entice for viewership totals so I get it-- yet it so much needed--the story of how one utilizes their body like an instrument, a well trained one--to express their inner thoughts and imagination. It starts with branding--how can highlight the combination of both athleticism and artistry--how they are are equal partners and how one, for the form to come alive, doesn't overwhelm or override the other? Appreciate of a national company putting the focus on dancers, on movement and on the process of embodying actions. It seems, from little I see so far and one I look forward to viewing, that the focus is on SAB yet should we be celebrating a process that looks at people's legs like they are objects? I know the history of the form invites this but can we also reshift how we look at how we can teach the form? There is value in how the form was taught since it the language is universal but does it put focus on "right" and" wrong" rather than what movement invites--to physicalize our inner rhythm and sensations? Thank you for listening.
